        // The difference is $a_{n+(n-1)/2} - a_{(n-1)/2}$.
        // This is not $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // The problem is that the elements $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$ and $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are not necessarily the classes themselves.
        //
        // The solution is indeed $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // We can always form two classes $C_1$ and $C_2$ such that $a_{n-1}$ is the median of $C_1$ and $a_n$ is the median of $C_2$.
        //
        // Let $C_1$ be $\{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$ and $C_2$ be $\{a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
