        //
        // The solution is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // This is a known result for similar problems.
        // The $n$-th element and $(n+1)$-th element (1-indexed) in the sorted array are $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$ (0-indexed).
        //
        // Consider the $2n$ students sorted: $s_1 \le s_2 \le \dots \le s_{2n}$.
        // We want to partition them into two classes $C_A$ and $C_B$, each with an odd number of students.
        // Let $m_A$ be the median of $C_A$ and $m_B$ be the median of $C_B$.
        // We want to minimize $|m_A - m_B|$.
        //
        // The minimum possible difference is $s_{n+1} - s_n$ (using 1-indexed notation for sorted array).
        // In 0-indexed notation, this is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // To achieve this, we can construct the classes as follows:
        // Let $C_A = \{s_n\}$ and $C_B = \{s_1, \dots, s_{n-1}, s_{n+1}, \dots, s_{2n}\}$.
        // This is not valid because $C_B$ has $2n-1$ students, which is odd. But $C_A$ has 1 student, which is odd.
        // The median of $C_A$ is $s_n$.
        // The median of $C_B$ is $s_{n+1}$ (if $2n-1$ students, median is $( (2n-1)+1 )/2 = n$-th element of $C_B$).
        // The elements of $C_B$ are $s_1, \dots, s_{n-1}, s_{n+1}, \dots, s_{2n}$.
        // The $n$-th element of $C_B$ is $s_{n+1}$.
        // So the medians are $s_n$ and $s_{n+1}$.
        // The difference is $s_{n+1} - s_n$.
        // This construction is always valid.
        //
        // Class A: $\{a_{n-1}\}$ (size 1, median $a_{n-1}$)
        // Class B: $\{a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$ (size $2n-1$, median $a_n$)
        //
        // Let's verify the median of Class B.
        // Class B has $2n-1$ elements. Its median is the $((2n-1)+1)/2 = n$-th element when sorted.
        // The elements of Class B, in sorted order, are $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // The $n$-th element (1-indexed) is $a_n$ (0-indexed).
        // So, the median of Class B is $a_n$.
        //
        // This construction always works and gives a difference of $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        // Since $a_n - a_{n-1}$ is the smallest possible difference between any two adjacent elements in the sorted array,
        // and we have shown that we can achieve this difference, it must be the minimum.
        //
        // The logic is sound. The answer is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.

        std::cout << a[n] - a[n - 1] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

